==English==
{{wp}}

===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|en|a capella|acapella}}

===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|it|[[alla]] [[cappella]]||in the manner of the [Sistine] chapel}}, referring to non-instrumental choirs.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ˌæ.kəˈpɛl.ə/|/ˌæ.kæˈpɛl.ə/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/ˌɑ kəˈpɛl.ə/}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɛlə}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-a_cappella.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|head=a cappella}}

# {{lb|en|music}} A vocal performance with no [[instrumental]] [[accompaniment]].

===Adverb===
{{en-adv|head=a cappella|-}}

# {{lb|en|music}} In a manner of a [[choir]] with no [[instrumental]] [[accompaniment]]; literally, "in the style of the (Sistine) Chapel (in Rome)", such as a musical Mass done ''a cappella''. {{defdate|from late 19th c.}}<ref name=SOED>Brown, Lesley, ed. ''The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary.'' 5th. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2003.</ref>
#: {{ux|en|Groups of teens singing '''a cappella''' on street corners got recording contracts.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete|music}} In ''[[alla breve]]'' time.

